<node id="Acquisitions">
  <data key="d0">Acquisitions</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Acquisitions refer to the process where one company purchases or takes over another, leading to various outcomes and impacts on the acquiring company. This business event can result in goodwill and intangible assets for the acquiring company, as well as incremental charges such as amortization of purchased intangible assets. Acquisitions can also impact a company's operations and its ability to integrate new businesses, as seen in the case of AMD. They are an important element of a company's strategy, involving the pursuit and integration of new technologies and businesses from external sources. However, acquisitions come with risks, including failure to realize expected revenues and returns from the acquired businesses, as well as the challenges of managing growth effectively, as demonstrated by Arm's external growth strategies. Additionally, acquisitions can lead to a more concentrated customer base, which may pose further risks and considerations for the acquiring company. Overall, acquisitions are a complex aspect of corporate strategy that can have significant financial and operational implications for the companies involved.&lt;SEP&gt;Acquisitions refer to the process of obtaining control over another company, often involving significant risks and uncertainties.&lt;SEP&gt;Acquisitions involve the purchase of businesses or assets to expand a company’s operations or market reach and can pose various financial and operational risks.&lt;SEP&gt;Acquisitions involve the purchase of businesses or assets to expand a company’s operations or market reach and can pose various financial and operational risks.&lt;SEP&gt;Acquisitions refer to the process of obtaining control over another company, often involving significant risks and uncertainties.&lt;SEP&gt;Acquisitions refer to the financial transactions whereby one entity purchases another, impacting cash flow and reported earnings.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-158df076948257685462bdd5a2ffcd95&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-625ca1cf50e3b24380c8601c96bdd7a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-531a2d4da0efcbaa075b41456e2d3536&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3a29194982b15aafff922b31789e91ea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-737963f5a4aa4c7ac5ff75bd66cabe60&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-adf3cdd028d63a6900c51e0d73fc800e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b07cc11b6e49549f800863a0e198d15c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a09335734e89edd5d8f3e04bd3466cd8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-db288d888bd9fbe8abf743c9d16d17a9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-631a6b54dbb91e5cb5c2815bdebd68cc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aa412cb5c38ae9e212cc41c77cb5b6bb</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1777381653</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Divestitures">
  <data key="d0">Divestitures</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Divestitures are the selling of a subsidiary or other business unit, which can be associated with risks such as the inability to complete proposed transactions timely or at all.&lt;SEP&gt;Divestitures refer to the process of selling off a portion of a company, leading to recognized gains or losses during the closing adjustments of such transactions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-158df076948257685462bdd5a2ffcd95&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-34fac0adf4c8e15583c5a62a870fb1d5</data>
