</node>
<node id="Goodwill">
  <data key="d0">Goodwill</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Goodwill is an intangible asset that signifies the excess of the purchase price over the fair value of net assets acquired during a business combination. It embodies the value of a company above its tangible assets and is often associated with factors like brand reputation and customer relationships. Goodwill is predominantly recognized in the context of acquisitions and is not subject to amortization; instead, it must be reviewed periodically for impairment. This evaluation assesses whether the recorded value of goodwill has diminished due to various factors, including poor performance of the acquired entity or complications arising from the acquisition process.

The valuation of goodwill reflects the anticipated future economic benefits stemming from the synergies of acquired companies and unquantified resources that contribute to capacity for growth. For instance, it was documented at $3,707 million for the fiscal years 2025 and 2026 and recorded at $97,801 million as of February 1, 2026. Such valuations highlight the significance of goodwill in financial assessments and the overall growth potential of the acquiring entity.

Goodwill serves as a key indicator of an entity's growth potential derived from its acquisitions, emphasizing the inherent value placed on reputation, customer relationships, and other non-tangible resources. Moreover, it is crucial for companies to undertake goodwill impairment tests at least annually, ensuring that its recognized value remains aligned with current economic conditions and that any necessary write-offs are implemented promptly if impairment is identified.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-625ca1cf50e3b24380c8601c96bdd7a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-43a8f055527dad4e87136bbd01caf743&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8e2d85f7a44ae4d46a5296c95183929c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-adf3cdd028d63a6900c51e0d73fc800e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-25056dc4aba0a40a47c338bbf9630c33&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-706c3addabed1cbc496a03d35fbb0b1b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d780eacfb91e291d22055bf3aca31fa3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b8b46fa35ec37b9bd74df50bd6a347ff&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b02dd03910eba2f64d7717819c0ef1bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-631a6b54dbb91e5cb5c2815bdebd68cc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b38febc44090948b4632a44869ab7045&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-34fac0adf4c8e15583c5a62a870fb1d5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c5e7cc3c7c57e107c4d688872735f76a</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1777382537</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Intangible Assets">
  <data key="d0">Intangible Assets</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Intangible Assets are defined as non-physical assets that provide value to businesses and contribute to their ability to generate future economic benefits. Key examples of intangible assets include patents, trademarks, goodwill, licenses, software, customer contracts, and developed technology. These assets play a vital role in a company’s operational success, enhancing its competitive advantage in the market.

Intangible assets are primarily distinguished from tangible assets due to their lack of physical substance. Unlike tangible assets, intangible assets are not amortized if they possess indefinite useful lives. Instead, they are subject to impairment reviews to ensure their recorded value reflects their true worth within financial statements.

The valuation of intangible assets is particularly relevant in the context of business combinations and overall company assessments. In specific instances, it has been noted that the total valuation of intangible assets reached approximately $30,302 million as of February 1, 2026, with a slight increase to $32,273 million noted for subsequent assessments. These figures illustrate the substantial economic impact that intangible assets can have on an organization’s financial positioning over time.

In summary, intangible assets encompass a wide range of non-physical entities crucial for business operations and valuations, playing a significant role in the overall economic landscape of companies.&lt;SEP&gt;Intangible Assets are non-physical assets subject to valuation and estimation for accounting purposes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-625ca1cf50e3b24380c8601c96bdd7a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-25056dc4aba0a40a47c338bbf9630c33&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b8b46fa35ec37b9bd74df50bd6a347ff&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-631a6b54dbb91e5cb5c2815bdebd68cc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b38febc44090948b4632a44869ab7045&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-49ecc61fbb17ccb3a4f86faecc7dbe50&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c5e7cc3c7c57e107c4d688872735f76a</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1777382510</data>
