  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Costs of Revenues">
  <data key="d0">Costs of Revenues</data>
  <data key="d1">financialmetric</data>
  <data key="d2">Costs of Revenues refer to the expenses directly associated with the production and sale of goods or services, reported in the company's financial statements.&lt;SEP&gt;Costs of revenues represent the expenses directly associated with generating the Company's revenue.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-37906de44c22f23501372f2b90cd5aa7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c0f7533f1c0231555ac5ae30f4d37842</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1777306896</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Stock Repurchase Program">
  <data key="d0">Stock Repurchase Program</data>
  <data key="d1">program</data>
  <data key="d2">The Stock Repurchase Program is an initiative aimed at repurchasing the company's own shares to address potential dilution caused by equity incentive plans and to return excess cash to stockholders. The program has a significant financial framework, allowing for a total of up to $10 billion in stock buybacks. As of June 30, 2025, there is $5.03 billion remaining in the allocation for these repurchases.

This program serves multiple purposes, including enhancing shareholder value, managing capital effectively, and reinforcing investor confidence by demonstrating the company's commitment to returning excess cash to its investors. The buybacks are subject to various operational priorities, thereby allowing the company to balance its financial strategies with its business needs effectively. Overall, the Stock Repurchase Program exemplifies the company's approach to capital management and shareholder engagement through strategic share repurchases.&lt;SEP&gt;The Stock Repurchase Program allows KLAC to buy back shares of its common stock, with no expiration date.&lt;SEP&gt;The Stock Repurchase Program allows KLAC to buy back its shares as authorized by its Board of Directors.&lt;SEP&gt;The Stock Repurchase Program is an initiative authorized by the Board of Directors to repurchase shares of common stock.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bfac3dde6482c2f8fd9ea0e0c659c15b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d34b219513d1d4953f831b7693287834&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0e0837ab88a60a72e576353a5fe0398b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f1d26aff29032e66965549a44d8a5643&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ab4fed2451ba98a9b8f9ac6037703d67&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0292dbc49bc4382dc3bccb8e9b403c95&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e87a4f351685e936b673b5d8beb0687a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5ff8c5ead4252ae2a31532cc82caa936</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1777382510</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Revolving Credit Facility">
  <data key="d0">Revolving Credit Facility</data>
  <data key="d1">financialinstrument</data>
  <data key="d2">The Revolving Credit Facility is a financial instrument and part of a company's capital structure, allowing the entity to borrow funds up to a certain limit as outlined in the Credit Agreement. It serves as a line of credit, enabling the company to maintain compliance with financial covenants if necessary. The facility has a maturity date of July 3, 2030, and offers the option to borrow up to $1.50 billion. It is mentioned in KLAC's report related to liquidity and capital resources. The Revolving Credit Facility is unsecured, with an earlier maturity date of June 8, 2027, also allowing borrowings up to $1.50 billion. This financial agreement provides flexibility for the company to access funds as needed, up to the specified amount.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bfac3dde6482c2f8fd9ea0e0c659c15b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bb113ac9e0cc9e74e5cc817ec0cd9a79&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6e39760d10a53b7326a952678788b4f5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f8cb9583c9766314f3cbadb2fe74821b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d34b219513d1d4953f831b7693287834&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a23fd7a348fc3f448641e9ef7d5be33a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6914852673b586e472efa313d90a7cbf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fcbd467e0d3d2d1e90e50929e4ef4372&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6430e92774e5a3f258ef2544910d4dd5</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1777307838</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
